04677nam a22005175i 9780774855259DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748552597 a10.59962/97807748552592doi  a(DE-B1597)661956  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE99.B39 ǂb K73 2006eb 7aART0410002bisacsh04a971.1/100497941 aKramer, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSwitchbacks :bArt, Ownership, and Nuxalk National Identity /cJennifer Kramer. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (168 p.) :b2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue: The Repatriation of the Nuxalk Echo Mask -- tIntroduction -- tThe History of Bella Coola: A History of Theft -- t“Selling Out” or “Buying In”? Identity Politics and Art Objectification in Bella Coola -- tPrivileged Knowledge versus Public Education: Tensions at Acwsalcta, the Nuxalk Nation “Place of Learning” -- tPhysical and Figurative Repatriation: Case Studies of the Nuxalk Echo Mask and the Nuxalk Sun Mask -- tTheft Inside and Out: The Making of a Theory -- tConclusions: Articulating Nuxalk National Identity -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSwitchbacks explores how the Nuxalk of Bella Coola, British Columbia, negotiate such complex questions as: Who owns culture? How should culture be transmitted to future generations? Where does selling and buying Nuxalk art fit into attempts to regain control of heritage? To answer these questions, Jennifer Kramer undertook participant observation at Nuxalk artists’ studios, in the Nuxalk-run band school’s cultural education classes, and during the everyday activities of Nuxalk in their homes. She charts the fluid character of tangible material culture (such as masks and other regalia) and intangible material culture (such as songs and dances) as they moved in and out of the cultural education curriculum, the Western art market, and the Western legal system. In addition, Kramer analyzes the ambivalent reactions of the Nuxalk to ownership, appropriation, and repatriation of Nuxalk culture. The Nuxalk oscillate between essential stances, a process Kramer likens to "switchbacks" on a mountain road. Through these recurrent movements they create, recreate, and validate contemporary Nuxalk identity. Kramer demonstrates that loss of cultural objects proves that Nuxalk culture is valuable through external affirmation. In this way, the Nuxalk use their cultural patrimony to assert their collective national identity. At stake are not only definitions of alienable and inalienable property but also a unified national identity that affords the Nuxalk a strong position from whence to reclaim traditional territory and regain self-determination in British Columbia. Switchbacks will appeal to scholars and students interested in questions of cultural ownership and identity in general, and in Nuxalk culture in particular.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aART / Native American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485525940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774855259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774855259/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-12772